 great puzzle of the Cold War, and in this book, the product of nearly twenty years of work, Trachtenberg tries to solve it.The answer, he says, has to do with the German question, especially with the German nuclear question. These issues lay at the heart of the Cold War, and a relatively stable peace took shape only when they were resolved. The book develops this argument by telling a story--a complex story involving many issues of detail, but focusing always on the central question of how a stable international system came into being during the Cold War period. A Constructed Peace will be of interest not just to students of the Cold War, but to people concerned with the problem of war and peace, and in particular with the question of how a stable international order can be constructed, even in our own day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNuclear weaponsxInternational cooperation. 0aPeace. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAtomic Energy Act.  aAttlee, Clement.  aBalance of payments.  aBohlen, Charles.  aBurke, Arleigh.  aCuban Missile Crisis.  aDouglas, Lewis.  aEden, Anthony.  aEuratom.  aForward defense.  aHarriman, Averell.  aIran.  aJoint Chiefs of Staff (JCS).  aKaysen, Carl.  aLeMay, Curtis.  aMassive retaliation.  aMolotov, Vjacheslav.  aNATO nuclear force.  aNonaggression pact.  aOder-Neisse Line.  aPolaris MRBM.  aPredelegation.  aPreemption.  aRosenberg, David.  aSchuman, Robert.  aStrategic balance.  aTruman Doctrine (1947).  aTurkey.  aWestern European Union (WEU).08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400843459zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400843459423Coveruhttps: